A Chrome developer tool conundrum!

The issue is likely due to how the website you're trying to open the developer tools on (`https://mnsw.pro/`) handles keyboard events. Specifically, it seems that the website is capturing the `Ctrl + Shift + I` shortcut and preventing it from reaching Chrome.

This is a common technique used by some websites to prevent users from opening the developer tools or accessing certain functionality. It's not a Chrome-specific issue, but rather a client-side JavaScript problem.

To bypass this restriction, you can try the following workarounds:

1. **Use the Chrome menu**: Instead of using the shortcut, you can open the Chrome developer tools by going to `View` > `Developer` > `Developer Tools` (or use the shortcut `Ctrl + Shift + J` on Windows/Linux or `Cmd + Opt + I` on Mac). This way, you're not relying on the keyboard shortcut.
2. **Inspect Element from the Address Bar**: Right-click on an element on the page, select "Inspect" or "Inspect Element" from the context menu, and a new Chrome developer tools window will open.
3. **Use a User Script**: You can create a user script to inject a script that allows the developer tools to open. You can use a userscript manager like Tampermonkey (Chrome extension) or Greasemonkey (Firefox extension). Here's an example script you can use:
```javascript
// ==UserScript==
// @name         Allow Developer Tools on mnsw.pro
// @namespace    http://tampermonkey.net/
// @version      0.1
// @description  Allow Developer Tools on mnsw.pro
// @author       You
// @match        https://mnsw.pro/*
// @grant        none
// ==/UserScript==

(window.addEventListener('load', function() {
  document.addEventListener('keydown', function(event) {
    if (event.ctrlKey && event.shiftKey && event.keyCode === 105) {
      // Open Developer Tools
      chrome.devtools.open();
    }
  });
}));
```
Load the script on the mnsw.pro website and then press `Ctrl + Shift + I` to open the developer tools.

Remember to exercise caution when using user scripts, as they can have unintended consequences. Always read the scripts carefully and test them in a sandbox environment before using them on actual websites.

